@shredhead408 This is the SNES era were talking about.

If a computer programmer decided to become a game developer they were pretty much seen as failures throwing their financial lives away. If you wanted money, you got a "real" job.

Nowadays they're seen as prestigious and successful (even the unsuccessful hacks), but back then, most developers just loved playing video games and wanted to make their own. Getting paid for it (poorly, I might add), just let them do what they love and live.

